  "prompt": "How much does getting a patent cost?",
  "response": "The cost of getting a patent can vary widely depending on several factors, including the type of patent (utility, design, or plant), the complexity of the invention, the geographical scope of the patent protection, and whether you hire a patent attorney. Here is a general breakdown:\n\n1. **Filing Fees:** The basic filing fee charged by the United States Patent and Trademark Office (USPTO) for a utility patent is typically around $300 for a small entity as of 2023. Fees can be reduced for micro-entities and increase for large entities.\n\n2. **Search and Examination Fees:** The USPTO charges additional fees for searching and examining the patent application, which can bring the costs to around $600 for small entities and more for larger entities.\n\n3. **Attorney Fees:** Hiring a patent attorney can significantly increase the cost but also greatly improve the chances of successfully obtaining a patent. Attorney fees for preparing and filing a patent application typically range from $5,000 to $10,000, depending on the complexity of the application.\n\n4. **Maintenance Fees:** If the patent is granted, there are ongoing maintenance fees to keep the patent enforceable, which could be several thousand dollars over the life of the patent.\n\n5. **Additional Costs:** There may be other potential costs, such as drafting fees, drawing fees, and foreign filing costs if you decide to seek protection outside of the United States. \n\nOverall, the total cost for obtaining a patent can range from a few thousand dollars for a relatively simple invention to tens of thousands of dollars for more complex inventions and extensive professional services.",
